<HEADLINE>
<P>
LOS ANGELES CITY HALL'S PILOT PROJECT TO RECYCLE WASTEPAPER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
As the sponsor of the City Hall pilot recycled paper program, we feel compelled 
to correct the many misstatements of fact in your article ("China Recycling 
Program a Paper Tiger," Metro, Dec. 3) and to affirm the excellent efforts of 
both the City of Los Angeles General Services Department and the city employees 
in making this project successful. 
</P>
<P>
This 6-month pilot was funded at considerable expense entirely by China Paper 
Partners. It tested a unique concept of separating, collecting and recycling 
mixed paper and represented the first phase of a project to build a de-inking 
pulp mill in Tianjin, China. 
</P>
<P>
The intent was to finish the feasibility study in June, break ground in August, 
and be able to ship Los Angeles wastepaper to the mill when it was finished. 
Unfortunately, the difficulty in relying on foreign markets for recycling that 
the United States should be undertaking itself was dramatically underscored by 
last summer's political events in China. 
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, Los Angeles made a good faith commitment to explore an innovative 
and needed means of recycling mixed paper. Neither party walked away from the 
program. I would like to correct several points: 
</P>
<P>
1. Conservatree Paper Co. and China Paper partners did not "lose interest in" 
or "abandon" the program in the spring of 1989. Mayor Tom Bradley notified 
employees about the program by letter in late February. 
</P>
<P>
Several meetings were conducted with the entire custodial services staff in 
April and May. China Paper Partners launched a follow-up employee education 
campaign throughout City Hall in early May, 1989, with a second letter of 
instruction from the mayor. 
</P>
<P>
With the assistance of the Los Angeles Conservation Corps, practically every 
employee work station in City Hall was visited, with program materials 
distributed and program operations explained on a one-to-one basis. This was 
supplemented by decals on all recycling and refuse bins, as well as posters in 
every elevator lobby. 
</P>
<P>
2. City's Hall's existing white paper and newspaper recycling programs were 
never discontinued. Rather, our mixed paper recycling program was added to the 
system. 
</P>
<P>
3. China Paper Partners was not in the business of buying and selling 
wastepaper. This would occur only if the pilot project succeeded and a mill 
were established in China. 
</P>
<P>
4. The collection program resulted in more than two-thirds of the waste stream 
being collected for recycling from both Transamerica and City Hall, more than 
twice the collection rate of programs previously judged successful. 
</P>
<P>
China Paper partners briefed the mayor's office, the General Services 
Department, and Councilwoman Ruth Galanter's office, as well as your newspaper, 
in October and November regarding the status of the program and the uncertainty 
of the situation in China. 
</P>
<P>
Innovative ventures such as this are complex, particularly when international 
political and business interests are mixed. The Chinese government remains 
deeply interested in this project. 
</P>
<P>
It is only after our November visit to China and time to review the complicated 
situation with planned investing institutions that we have had the information 
necessary to determine the next steps. Unfortunately, this includes the 
realization that our ability to proceed in China will be delayed. Therefore, we 
have laid the groundwork to extend the program to other countries, if 
necessary. 
</P>
<P>
Despite the current political problems hampering the program in China, we 
remain deeply committed to designing and implementing environmentally sound and 
effective business solutions to a serious environmental problem. 
</P>
<P>
ALAN DAVIS 
</P>
<P>
Chairman 
</P>
<P>
China Paper Partners Inc. 
</P>
<P>
San Francisco 
</P>
</TEXT>
