<HEADLINE>
<P>
DR. JOYCE BROTHERS: EASE THE MOVE FOR 4-YEAR-OLD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DR. JOYCE BROTHERS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DEAR DR. BROTHERS: We deliberately postponed moving so it wouldn't interrupt 
our 10-year-old's school year, but now we're amazed at how upset our 4-year-old 
is. Since he didn't have much to interrupt in the way of friends or 
commitments, we thought it would be relatively unimportant to him. He's become 
very anxious and is suffering from nightmares. What are we doing wrong? -- D.P. 
</P>
<P>
DEAR D.P.: Child psychologists point out that often when little children see 
all the boxes being tied up ready to be sent away and possessions being packed 
or thrown out, it makes them fear that this may also happen to them. It is 
important to reassure your child that he's coming with you. Help him to look 
forward to being part of the family in a new town and meeting new friends. 
</P>
<P>
After you move, don't redecorate your child's room for a while, and arrange 
furniture as it was before. Dr. Tiffany Field of the University of Miami 
Medical School says that having the old furniture in place can be like a 
security blanket. 
</P>
<P>
Remember not to throw away all the old toys and books. Children need a sense of 
continuity, and it's vital to be able to hang on to some objects that bring 
comfort and solace. 
</P>
<P>
DEAR DR. BROTHERS: When I was in my second year of college, I cheated on an 
exam and was caught by the teacher and expelled. Eventually, I enrolled at 
another school and got my degree, but I've never gotten over the feeling of 
shame. It almost led me to suicide. My parents thought I was overreacting, even 
though they were very angry at the time. I know lots of kids cheat, and I 
wonder if my reaction is normal. -- W.F. 
</P>
<P>
DEAR W.F.: Shame is a powerful emotion because it cuts through to one's basic 
sense of self. Certainly, shame would be a normal feeling after what happened 
to you. 
</P>
<P>
Shame becomes dangerous when it starts to color one's most basic idea about 
what one is or how worthy one is. You may need counseling to rid yourself of 
this past error if you feel shame every time someone rebukes you and if, 
despite beginning again and getting your degree, you still feel guilty and 
worry that you're not to be trusted. 
</P>
<P>
Feelings of shame are often at the root of what may seem like irrational rage, 
according to some experts, and shame has been shown to play a key role in many 
cases of family violence. 
</P>
<P>
The best antidote to shame is to get it in enough perspective to be able to 
laugh at it. After all, this is something that happened a long time ago. Talk 
with someone about it. Don't keep it to yourself any longer. You've learned 
from your mistakes and that is what's important now. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA012090-0044 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 164542 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
January 20, 1990, Saturday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
View; Part F; Page 21; Column 4; View Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
731 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
BOB GREENE: STRAIGHT FROM CELEBRITIES' LIPS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BOB GREENE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Lots of people collect autographs. It's a fairly common hobby -- seeking the 
signatures of famous men and women. 
</P>
<P>
Jilly Eddy, of Walnut Creek, Calif., has a similar hobby. Similar, but quite 
different. Eddy collects lip prints. 
</P>
<P>
"Lip prints are just what they sound like," said Eddy, who sells appliances for 
Sears. "They're prints of people's lips." Lip prints, she said, are also 
referred to as "lipographs." 
</P>
<P>
Eddy, 44, said she has been collecting lip prints for almost 10 years. "I keep 
them in a lip print book," she said. "It's pretty much like an autograph book, 
except it's filled with people's lip prints." 
</P>
<P>
On each page of her lip print book is the lip print of a different person. "A 
lip print is much more personal than an autograph," Eddy said. "People sign 
their names lots of times. They sign checks and stuff every day. They don't 
even think about it. A lip print, though, is special. You have to press your 
lips against a piece of paper. And each lip print is as individual as a 
fingerprint. No two lip prints are the same. But a lip print is much more 
sensuous than a fingerprint." 
</P>
<P>
In order to give Eddy a lip print, a person must first put lipstick on his or 
her mouth (more about that in a moment). Then there is a certain technique. . 
.well, let's have Eddy explain it herself: 
</P>
<P>
"You put the lipstick on. You keep your mouth open just a bit when you're 
pressing it onto the paper. While you do it, you should pretend that you're 
kissing someone you really like -- pretend that you're giving that person a 
good kiss. Without any tongue, though -- that leaves a smudge." 
</P>
<P>
The results, she said, are beautiful. 
</P>
<P>
"I like lip prints from a person who has nice, full lips. Lips that have a nice 
shape to them. The best kind of upper lip, I think, has a bowed shape, with an 
indentation in the top. The best lower lips are just a little fuller than the 
upper lip." 
</P>
<P>
She claims she can tell something about a person just by his or her lip print: 
</P>
<P>
"I have found that a person with full lips usually likes to talk a lot -- 
people whose lip prints are full are gabbers. People with thin lips tend to be 
more conservative." 
</P>
<P>
Eddy collects lip prints from both men and women. This sometimes presents a 
problem. As we have noted, to give a lip print, a person must put on lipstick. 
</P>
<P>
"Women tend to love the idea," Eddy said. "They really get into doing this. I 
tell them to put on a really bright red lipstick. Most women wear peach 
lipstick or pink lipstick; but for a lip print to look good, I tell the women 
to put on the kind of lipstick that Marilyn Monroe and Jayne Mansfield used to 
wear. Bright, bright red, really spread over the lips thickly. 
</P>
<P>
"Some men are willing to put lipstick on if they know it's for the purpose of a 
lip print. The others, though, I tell to kiss a woman who's wearing a lot of 
lipstick, and then to put their lip prints in my book while the women's 
lipstick is still on their lips. It's pretty easy: A man kisses a woman, then 
he kisses my book." 
</P>
<P>
Interestingly, this man-kisses-a-woman-then-kisses-the-book technique was first 
tried out on a rather well-known man: Johnny Cash. 
</P>
<P>
"I was living in Bellingham, Wash., at the time, and I was driving a limousine 
for a living," Eddy said. "I was driving Johnny Cash when he was in town, and I 
picked him up at the Holiday Inn; he was with his manager and his lead 
guitarist. He signed his autograph for me, and I told him that I would rather 
have his lip print. 
</P>
<P>
"He didn't say anything for a second, and then in this deep, deep voice he 
said: 'I don't wear lipstick.' So I said to him, 'Well, what you can do is kiss 
someone who does wear lipstick, and then kiss my book.' He said, 'Well, OK,' 
and he gave me a big kiss and then he kissed my lip print book. 
</P>
<P>
"Unfortunately, I was wearing this very expensive Estee Lauder nonsmudge 
lipstick that day, and because it was nonsmudge, not all that much of it got on 
Johnny Cash's lips, so his lip print in my book is sort of faint." 
</P>
<P>
One of the nice things about collecting lip prints, Eddy said, is that -- 
unlike autographs -- a lip print from a non-celebrity can be as good as a lip 
print from a celebrity. With an autograph, it's how famous the person is; with 
a lip print, it's how good the person's lips are. 
</P>
<P>
And, no, Eddy said, there is absolutely no way to tell from a person's lip 
print whether or not that person is a good kisser. 
</P>
</TEXT>
