<HEADLINE>
<P>
EAGLE TACKLE HELLER SUES BAKER, VIKINGS FOR EYE INJURY IN 1988 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
MINNEAPOLIS 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Minnesota Vikings and former Viking player Al (Bubba) Baker were sued 
Friday by Philadelphia Eagle offensive tackle Ron Heller over an eye injury 
Heller suffered during a game in 1988. 
</P>
<P>
Harry Sieben Jr., a Minneapolis attorney who filed the suit in Hennepin County 
District Court, said the case involves "gross negligence, aggravated conduct 
and reckless disregard of the rights of another person." 
</P>
<P>
Sieben alleged the Vikings were negligent in supervising and training Baker. 
</P>
<P>
The suit, which seeks in excess of $50,000, alleges Baker poked Heller in the 
eye in an altercation in the second quarter of a Sept. 25, 1988 game, causing 
permanent injury to Heller's left cornea. Heller was hospitalized for five 
days, but was able to play the rest of the 1988 season and was a regular this 
season. 
</P>
<P>
Baker, now with the Cleveland Browns, was served papers at his home in 
Westlake, Ohio. 
</P>
</TEXT>
