<HEADLINE>
<P>
FIDELITY FINANCIAL SELLING STOCK BACK TO HAMMOND CO. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JAMES S. GRANELLI, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
NEWPORT BEACH 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Irvine-based Fidelity National Financial Inc. said Friday that it will sell its 
23.6% interest in the Hammond Co. and that Hammond will pay $1.9 million to 
purchase the Fidelity stake. 
</P>
<P>
The agreement ends seven months of sporadic talks between the two firms about 
establishing closer business ties or a possible merger. 
</P>
<P>
Hammond directors and shareholders now will consider turning the publicly 
traded firm into a private company, said company Chairman Thomas T. Hammond. 
About 10 of the Newport Beach company's 400 shareholders own about 60% of the 
firm, he said. 
</P>
<P>
Hammond said the company will use its cash reserves to purchase the stock. 
</P>
<P>
After a recent meeting, Fidelity executives decided that "a mutually agreeable 
business operation wouldn't be forthcoming, and we didn't want to pursue 
Hammond in a hostile nature," said Frank P. Willey, Fidelity's executive vice 
president and general counsel. 
</P>
<P>
Fidelity, a title insurance firm operating in 31 states, agreed to sell its 
stake to Hammond for $4.83 a share -- the estimated price Fidelity paid for the 
Hammond stock. 
</P>
<P>
"We never got around to talking seriously about an acquisition," Willey said. 
"Our conceptual discussions were far enough apart." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
