</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
BUYER BEWARE? NOT IF HOME GETS INSPECTION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ROBERT OSTMANN JR., Robert Ostmann Jr. is a regular contributor to Orange 
County Life. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Seems simple: to check the sink plumbing for leaks, turn on the water and look 
for drips. Not quite, says Jack Gerwick. 
</P>
<P>
"You have to turn just the hot water on and let it run. That makes the pipes 
expand and leaks show up right away. If you just used cold water, you might not 
see them," Gerwick said as he leaned inside a cabinet to feel a drain pipe for 
tell-tale moisture. 
</P>
<P>
Gerwick is a house sleuth for Inspector Homes, a Laguna Beach home inspection 
service. On this recent afternoon, he crawled, climbed, peered and prodded his 
way through an Irvine tract home, meticulously recording each flaw he ferreted 
out. 
</P>
<P>
Armed with his five-page report, the people buying this house will know exactly 
what they're walking into on moving day. 
</P>
<P>
Real estate agents say home inspectors are indispensable for home buyers, most 
of whom probably think a ground fault interrupter is something that stops 
earthquakes. 
</P>
<P>
"In real estate the main thing used to be location, location, location. Now 
everybody wants disclosure, disclosure, disclosure," said Cheri Jessup, an 
agent with Whitewater Realty in San Clemente. 
</P>
<P>
"The standard form that sellers fill out now really doesn't tell all that much 
about the house. A home inspection lets the buyer see in great detail what 
shape the house is in. And it gives the seller much more protection down the 
line because there are no surprises." 
</P>
<P>
The dozens of home inspection companies in Orange County offer scrutiny of 
varying thoroughness at prices that range from about $115 to as much as $400. 
</P>
<P>
Buyers of existing homes generally line up a home inspection company through 
their real estate agents. Buyers of new homes or those buying existing homes 
without an agent can find inspection companies in the phone directory, through 
recommendations from friends or neighbors or through the California Real Estate 
Assn. in Sacramento, a trade organization that provides standards and education 
for member companies. 
</P>
<P>
While home inspection clients are mainly buyers of existing homes, buyers of 
new homes can use an inspection to head off a lot of hassles. 
</P>
<P>
"If the house is not done right, it's not right," said Vince Von Lenhoff, 
co-owner with his wife, Carol of Inspector Homes. 
</P>
<P>
"Why should a buyer have to fight for a year saying all the windows don't open 
right. By inspecting it ahead of time, he can have it right there in the paper 
work from the start and have a much better chance of getting it fixed." 
</P>
<P>
Sellers also can benefit from getting the inside story on their property. 
</P>
<P>
"Someone may have lived in a house for 25 years, but they can't see some things 
that may be wrong," Von Lenhoff said. "But if somebody unbiased from outside 
comes in, they can find the little leak under the sink or the foundation crack 
in the garage." 
</P>
<P>
The seller can use this information to get the house in the best condition for 
sale, Von Lenhoff said. 
</P>
<P>
A detailed inspection of a typical three-bedroom home can take about two hours 
and includes a close look at the home's construction, electrical supply, 
plumbing, fireplaces, insulation, heating and cooling equipment, appliances and 
roof. Inspectors check things as simple as whether windows open easily or 
whether there is enough water pressure. 
</P>
<P>
Most inspection companies do not deal with solar heating and security systems, 
water purifiers, pool and spa construction and certain other equipment. They 
refer clients to firms that specialize in these areas. 
</P>
<P>
As Gerwick got ready to begin his recent inspection of the Irvine home, the 
buyers were absent. 
</P>
<P>
Buyers should insist on being present for the home inspection, Carol Von 
Lenhoff said. 
</P>
<P>
"If you're buying a house, you should take two hours off work and come to the 
inspection. That way we can explain things that are in the report. Something 
like 'crack in living room ceiling' might look bad on paper, but in person we 
can show that it's just a minor effect of normal settling. We can save the 
buyer the aggravation, tension and worry and make the transaction go a lot more 
smoothly." 
</P>
<P>
Gerwick, a general contractor for 30 years before he went to work for Inspector 
Homes last year, began his inspection in the kitchen. 
</P>
<P>
He opened drawers and windows, checked plumbing connections and tested 
electrical outlets to make sure they were grounded and wired properly. He 
switched on the garbage disposal and ran the dishwasher through an entire 
cycle. 
</P>
<P>
A pocket door was a little tough to open. "One little shaker (earthquake) can 
make one of these tough to open," Gerwick said. 
</P>
<P>
As he moved from room to room, Gerwick kept careful notes. 
</P>
<P>
"I try to be thorough but not nit-picky," he said. "I base the inspection on 
the age of the house. Something that might be normal for a 10-year-old house -- 
small cracks at the corners of doors or windows or drywall nails popped out 
after small earthquakes -- might be signs of trouble in a brand new home." 
</P>
<P>
Gerwick stuck his head inside the living room fireplace to make sure there were 
no gaps between the firebricks, that the damper worked and that there was no 
dangerous build-up of flammable creosote in the flue. 
</P>
<P>
He examined the ceiling in every room for evidence of water stains from roof 
leaks, and the walls for evidence of cracking that would indicate more than 
usual settling of the house. 
</P>
<P>
In the bathrooms, he flushed the toilets, checked them and other plumbing for 
leaks, and noted that an electrical outlet was not equipped with a ground fault 
interrupter, a device designed to prevent accidental electrical shocks around 
water. 
</P>
<P>
"The house was built before they were required," Gerwick said, "but I'll 
mention it anyway so the buyers are aware. It might be something they want to 
change." 
</P>
<P>
Occasionally, inspectors encounter homeowners who cover up problems. 
</P>
<P>
"Some people throw towels over the glass door of the shower. You look 
underneath and find a crack in the glass. If you find one sneaky thing like 
that, you look harder for other problems," Vince Von Lenhoff said. 
</P>
<P>
"I inspected the attic in one house and came down and asked the owner if she'd 
ever had any roof leaks. She said no. I said, 'Well, I'm not saying you're not 
telling the truth but there are buckets up there.' " 
</P>
<P>
Von Lenhoff said he once got a call from a buyer who asked why he hadn't been 
told about the secret room. "The previous owners had built a hidden room and 
sealed it with a panel that was screwed down. We had no idea it was there. An 
inspector is only as good as what he can see." 
</P>
<P>
Gerwick took great pains to see as much as he could get to in his inspection of 
the Irvine house. He crawled into the attic through a ceiling access panel and 
walked about in the darkness checking wiring, insulation and roof vents with 
his flashlight. 
</P>
<P>
In the garage, Gerwick inspected the furnace filter and gas connections. He 
manually turned on the heat and air conditioning to make sure they worked. He 
checked the water heater plumbing. He checked the electrical outlets and found 
one, a 220-volt outlet for a clothes dryer, that was dead. 
</P>
<P>
Gerwick clicked the garage door closer and found to his dismay that the huge 
door did not stop its descent when he tried to block it with his body. "That's 
a problem," he said. "Should have gone back up as soon as it hit me. Don't want 
kids or pets to get caught under it." He made a notation in his report. 
</P>
<P>
He took one turn around the outside of the house looking for improper drainage 
and foundation cracks. He found several hairline cracks but said those are 
normal. "I'm looking for cracks you can stick your little finger into." 
</P>
<P>
Then he headed for the last inspection: the roof. 
</P>
<P>
Vince Von Lenhoff said roof checks are especially important because roof 
repairs are expensive and appearances can be deceiving. 
</P>
<P>
"First thing I do when I come into the neighborhood is look at the roofs of the 
other houses. If you see a bunch of new roofs in a tract, you can suspect that 
the roof on the house you're inspecting is near the end of its life expectancy. 
</P>
<P>
"But you have to check even new roofs. I was on one, brand new, and found that 
it was laid improperly over an old wood shingle roof and someone had walked on 
it and cracked the new shingles. Brand new roof and it leaked." 
</P>
<P>
Gerwick completed his survey of the roof, finding a few places where shingles 
were missing and leaks were possible. 
</P>
<P>
Back on the ground, as he maneuvered his ladder in the front yard, he stepped 
into a rose bush and ripped a huge hole in his pants. 
</P>
<P>
He shrugged off the damage with a laugh. "That's just part of the job of trying 
to give the buyer a little peace of mind." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, At left: Jack Gerwick of Inspector Homes takes a look at an attic. 
Above: pocket-sized circuit tester is used to check wiring. Below: Gerwick, 
left, and Inspector Homes co-owners Carol and Vince Von Lenhoff go over a home 
in Irvine. MARK BOSTER / Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
HOUSING INSPECTIONS; INSPECTOR HOMES (COMPANY); INSPECTORS; HOUSING SALES; 
HOUSES 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA012090-0150 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 165443 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
January 20, 1990, Saturday, Orange County Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Orange County Life; Part N; Page 1; Column 1 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
1337 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
LIVING AGAIN IN GLASS HOUSES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By NANCY JO HILL 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Elyse Froehlich was overwhelmed the first time she made a nighttime visit to 
her nearly completed custom home in Capistrano Beach. Exterior lights glowed 
and twinkled through a 21-by-21-foot curved stairwell wall of jewel-like glass 
blocks, creating a stunning, dramatic effect. 
</P>
<P>
"It's difficult to understand what something like this is actually gonna be 
like from a drawing," Froehlich says. "The impact, it's like so strong. And 
when you come down from the top of the bridge (staircase) to the landing, it's 
just such a powerful experience." 
</P>
<P>
Froehlich, a painter, had told the architect that glass block was one of the 
elements that she and her husband, Richard, a cardiologist, really liked. And 
she wanted the house to function as a sculpture, an artwork in its own right. 
</P>
<P>
The result was a 6,000-square-foot house that incorporates glass block as a 
major design element throughout, giving this contemporary home with classical 
elements a flowing continuity. 
</P>
<P>
Glass blocks, which were at a peak of popularity in this country during the 
1920s and '30s, enjoyed a resurgence in the 1980s as homeowners and architects 
rediscovered this aesthetically pleasing and functional building material. 
</P>
<P>
Glass blocks are being used with increasing frequency in contemporary custom 
homes being designed in Orange County, according to local architects, designers 
and masons who install them. Tract-home designers are also beginning to 
incorporate glass block. One 133-unit tract of Huntington Beach homes will 
include thousands of glass blocks to provide diffused light while maintaining 
privacy. 
</P>
<P>
Glass blocks are being used for walls, facades, stairwells, windows and 
interior partitions, including curved shower stall walls. The blocks are 
durable and easy to maintain, and provide more security than regular glass 
because they are hard to break. And they are available in varied designs, 
ranging from clear to opaque, allowing a clear view, an obscured view or 
complete privacy. 
</P>
<P>
Blocks are also available in varied sizes, from four-inch-square to 
12-inch-square. Rectangular blocks are also available in some sizes. Prices 
vary from $3 for a small, simple block up to $100 apiece for glass blocks that 
are custom-etched. 
</P>
<P>
In most installations, however, labor is the biggest cost, ranging from $28 to 
$60 per square foot. Frequently masons must make tricky on-site adjustments to 
turn an architect's concept into a reality. 
</P>
<P>
The demand for glass blocks has gone up significantly, especially in the 
residential market, according to Richard Carey, architectural representative 
for the Angelus Block Co. of Orange. 
</P>
<P>
Angelus is a distributor for Pittsburg Corning Corp., the only U.S. 
manufacturer of glass blocks. He says his company has enjoyed "substantial 
increases every year." 
</P>
<P>
"Architects suddenly latched onto the product and started doing some very 
unique designs," Carey says. "A product like this allows them to design-in 
privacy and allow light and incorporate architectural elements that were never 
used, can't be done with other materials." 
</P>
<P>
"We almost use it in every appropriate project," says James Gartner of his 
Santa Ana firm, James Gartner &amp; Associates, Architects. "We're going back 
to the decorative style of architecture." 
</P>
<P>
He says people are returning to "a combination of contemporary and decorative 
(styles), and glass block seems to work in both cases. It works as a high-tech 
material, and it works as a decorative material." 
</P>
<P>
In the Froehlich home, for instance, the blocks do not have the cold feel that 
might be expected. Instead, the light that flows through is warm and soothing. 
</P>
<P>
In a large, white, ceramic-tile shower in the master bath, for instance, there 
are two windows made of eight-inch-square glass blocks. The window facing a 
neighboring house has textured blocks for privacy at a lower level and clear 
blocks higher up. The window facing the ocean has clear blocks and allows a 
person to shower while watching the waves. 
</P>
<P>
Also in the master bath, a whirlpool tub is surrounded by white ceramic tile 
and black marble. An eight-foot-long, glass-block window above the tub lets 
light in but provides privacy too. 
</P>
<P>
The eight-inch-square blocks used in the curved stairwell wall are a mix of 
clear blocks and ones with a wavy design that partly obscures the view of a 
neighboring house. Through the clear blocks, the sky and tall trees are 
visible,and there is a glimpse of the neighboring house. Columns of 
earth-colored caldura stone and a wool Berber carpet in a peach/mauve color add 
to the warm feeling. 
</P>
<P>
Froehlich's studio has an eight-foot-by-12-foot glass-block window with a 
special feature. Six windows that open are set into the rest. And in the living 
room and family room, 12-inch-square glass blocks are set into the wall about 
two feet apart, above French doors with a view of the ocean. 
</P>
<P>
"I think that the uniqueness of it isn't just the fact that it's glass block," 
says Jim Pepperell of Jim Pepperell Enterprises Inc. of Laguna Niguel, the 
general contractor on the Froehlich home. "It's all the different ways it's 
been used. It's just about covering the whole spectrum of any possible way you 
could use glass block." 
</P>
<P>
The cost of elegance is not cheap, however. The glass block and the 
installation of the curved stairwell wall alone cost about $19,000, according 
to Tom Justus of Justus Masonry, Cerritos. His company did the installation, 
which took about three weeks to complete. Special reinforcement of the wall 
brought the total cost to about $30,000. 
</P>
<P>
Less elaborate installations of glass blocks are more common. 
</P>
<P>
Arta Alexander of Fullerton wanted to brighten up a dark doorway. She had two 
narrow doors in the entry of her home replaced with one standard door and one 
vertical row of 7 1/2-inch-square glass blocks. Alexander, a landscape 
designer, is pleased with the result -- a warm, brighter entry and light for 
nearby planter. 
</P>
<P>
Designer Pete Rose of Balboa Pacific in Balboa was asked to create a design 
using glass block to brighten a remodeling effort by a development company on a 
Balboa home. In the master bath, he designed two pyramid-shaped windows that 
are mirror images on each side of a corner above the bath. There are four rows 
of 12-inch-square glass blocks in the windows, laid in stairstep fashion from 
five blocks on the bottom row to one at the top. 
</P>
<P>
The bathroom floor and walls are dark brown, gold and black slate, so the 
windows provide much-needed light. Another vertical row of three glass blocks 
is used on a slate divider between the tub and toilet. And in the bedroom, a 
five-foot-by-six-foot glass block window provides diffused light with privacy. 
The windows will be lighted at night with spotlights. 
</P>
<P>
He is also planning a counter that will have a wood top and a glass block base. 
A fluorescent light under the counter will shine down on the glass blocks. 
</P>
<P>
Ocean Pointe, a tract of 133 homes built closely together in Huntington Beach, 
features still more uses of glass block. Mike Araujo of Mike's Masonry, 
Huntington Beach, says he will use 14,000 glass blocks in the 83 homes being 
framed. 
</P>
<P>
Since neighboring houses are so close, a conventional kitchen window would 
provide only a view of someone else's wall. So the designers put two long 
vertical rows of eight-inch glass blocks over the cooktop. The result is light 
and airy. The blocks are also used for windows upstairs and near the 
first-floor powder room, and as curved windows in entries. 
</P>
<P>
In one model, a bath has three 12-inch blocks set into the wall above a mirror, 
about a foot apart. In a guest bedroom, three 12-inch blocks are set into the 
wall in a vertical row, about six inches apart. Another use is to place five 
12-inch blocks in a horizontal row, high on a bedroom wall and spaced about a 
foot apart. 
</P>
<P>
"What I like about it," says Araujo of glass block, "is the way the sun 
illuminates it." 
</P>
<P>
He says that when sunlight hits glass blocks just right, it's akin to looking 
at a kaleidoscope because of all the colors refracted in the glass. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Elyse Froehlich with curved stairwell. ; Photo, Glass blocks lend light 
to slate used in Newport Beach bathroom. GARY AMBROSE / Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
